metadata.name: The Grid #7
metadata.description:
The Grid is my third art to go live, the pen-like shapes are ordered by noise which decides if to draw a circle or a square, grid range is between 2x2 to 12x12.
This work was created using p5.js and love :)

metadata.name: KINJO! #228
metadata.description:
A celebration of my 1 year in the Tezos art space, KINJO is an experiment in pure abstraction and randomness. With a simple grid at its core, this piece attempts to play with lively colors, completely unique variations, and host the nice surprises that randomness can bring.

My intention when starting to work in the Tezos space was to play with the surrender of control in art, that idea had always fascinated me. In the beginning it was working with GAN, digitally painting a piece or processing my own photography, and sending it through my own frankensteined colab notebook. I was creating something and then trusting a process to rip it apart and create something new. I moved on to the Ganerations project, which was essentially gen art in layered pngs and processed through my GAN notebook. I found generative art and fxHash shortly after and have been incredibly thankful for the community here, as well as inspired every day by the new approaches I see from both new and established artists on the platform. I'm learning every day.

Gen art is the perfect place for me to express myself and explore the themes of control and trust with my work, and I thank you all for following along and supporting my work :)

metadata.name: PXL #127
metadata.description:
PXL is an exploration of video synthesis, each pixel containing 4 cells phasing between two values. This effect creates all sorts of interesting effects when scaled up, so enjoy the completely unique effect your optical illusion generates.

There is a 5% chance to generate a wave glitch in your pattern.

Color palettes:
80% Normal (Randomly Generated)
10% Monochrome
5% RGB
5% CMYK

Press 's' to save a png
Press 'm' to save a 10s mp4 (can take up to 2m to render)

metadata.name: Inertia #824
metadata.description:
This project will be reserved and free for 48 hours, for all the holders of any of my projects!

The amount of reserves for each user will be equal to the amount of all the token held at 13:00 CEST [UTC+2] (May 23)
(example: user holds 3 "Figment" and 2 "ACCUMULATOR", will be able to mint "Inertia" 5 times)

48h from now I will update the reserves list and burn the remaining tokens

WARINING: The reserves will expire 48h after the drop! And a price for the unlocked mintables will be set (unreserved mints will not be free).

---

"Inertia is a property of matter by which it continues in its existing state of rest or uniform motion in a straight line, unless that state is changed by an external force."

Particles are blasted from 2 to 4 sides of the canvas, each particle has its own mass and it has to traverse a friction-field, once it loses its momentum completely it stops and leaves a trace, adding or subtracting light from the canvas.

The friction-field has 18 possible mutation kinds.
Mutations are high-friction zones of various shapes.

Made just with JS on a canvas
right-click to save

metadata.name: A Less Traveled Path #103
metadata.description:
"I shall be telling this with a sigh
Somewhere ages and ages hence:
Two roads diverged in a wood, and I—
I took the one less traveled by,
And that has made all the difference."

- Robert Frost, The Road Not Taken



=========

Controls:
[1] set resolution to 1024x1024 (default)
[2] set resolution to 2048x2048 
[3] set resolution to 4096x4096
[0] set resolution to window size (might help on lower end computers)

[c] capture a screenshot at rendered resolution


Made with cables.gl, a node-based webgl environment
XALTED 2022

metadata.name: Monsoon #362
metadata.description:
Optimization. It's something that haunts all programmers. Including me. But no longer! Monsoon is a study into the optimization of particle systems for the web. Looking especially deep into dynamic grids and dynamic frame rates.

As for the piece itself, it's a reference to how busy this modern world is. How we're all constantly on the go, whether that is physically, or mentally. Almost feeling like a monsoon. A storm of information. A storm of life. A storm of work. A storm of thoughts. A storm of emotions. A storm of everything. And it's all so fast.

As are the particles. They're all moving around these cyclones of information. Glowing up like neon signs in a busy city. Moving so fast it's almost a blur. Forming into something greater than the sum of its parts.

metadata.name: Canevach #14
metadata.description:
Canevach started as a code golfing experiment, 280 characters of HTML, CSS and JavaScript producing pixelated patterns when copy-pasted in the address bar of a web browser.

The code has been adapted for the sake of entropy control and readability, but I tried to keep it as lean as possible to honour the code golfing spirit that initiated the project.

The artwork is generated by manipulating pixels directly through the Canvas API.

Colours are uniformly selected in RGB space, without any colour theory considerations. The only exception is for black, which is made more prominent by the way the algorithm is initiated.

Features
• Canvas size: 8x8 | 16x16 | 32x32 | 64x64 | 128x128
• Number of colours: 1 to 5

fx(hash) Generative Token by loackme

metadata.name: adrift #165
metadata.description:
Take your entire life, full as it is with the vastness of your lived experiences – and shape it into your cupped hands. Cherish this mesmerising world of yours as you would a ripe summer fruit, and behold at a glance its delicate yet dynamic balance — one change here or there, no matter how microscopic, affects the entire course of your world. 

How will you receive this world – its situations that overwhelm, its sights that awe, the catastrophes, the serenity, its steadfast commitment to the present? Will you look upon all of us here, adrift and fragile together, with love?


Adrift is a project that reminds us to make peace with our world – with all worlds – by stepping back to make space for an all-encompassing perspective.


------------


Created by Jacek Markusiewicz @jMarkusiewicz
Creative collaboration with Tender @tender_art

Click on the image for resolution options and to save a .png file. Saving higher resolutions may not work in some browsers; in these cases, right-click-save the image. All drawing and geometric methods are written by mrkswcz using javascript, except for the following:

The pseudorandom terrain generation uses Hydraulic-Erosion by Sebastian Lague, inspired by "Reconnaissance" by TENDER x Nat Sarkissian (MIT License).

For finding paths that simulate connections in terrain and potential locations of cities, a C# script was adapted from the article "Pathfinding Algorithms in C#" by Kristian Ekman published in Code Project licensed under The Code Project Open License (CPOL). The code was translated to javascript and simplified for performance.

Many pseudorandom effects are achieved with perlin-simplex by David Guttman and seedrandom by David Bau (both MIT Licenses)

For more information, please see the bundle.js.LICENSE.txt file included in the package.

The "heat death" event is a small tribute to lunarean's fxhash project. The code that generates the disintegration effect interprets a fragment of lunarean's code. Further contributions are its adaptation for 3d transformations and its recursive character that modifies certain parameters over time.

The project uses CPU for calculations and rendering – generating the image requires up to 500MB of free RAM. Testing was performed across browsers and devices, but please make sure it works on your device before minting. Note that there are minor colour-intensity differences between different browsers.

metadata.name: In Due Time #8
metadata.description:
“In Due Time” is a collaborative generative collection between artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria. Inspired by Wiederrecht’s mastery of line and Vittoria’s notable palette, this 1/1/250 series captures the present moment. It serves as a reminder that we are more similar than we are different, leveraging homogeneous shapes to create distinctive compositions.

Vittoria’s poem for the collection:

“In Due Time”
We will all become
Particles dancing
Across the skyline.

The artwork listed is indeed authentic, created by, and copyright to artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria; the purchase of this NFT is a purchase of the asset, not of the copyright.

-------------------------------------------

To save a high-resolution image for printing, click “open” under the image on the page for your token, and then hit:

Digits “1” through “9” to get an image that is 1000 through 9000px tall.  This may take a while, depending on the size and your computer, so please be patient.

metadata.name: possibleScapes #13
metadata.description:
When memory, photography and code interrelate.

The animated images, accumulations of other images, reveal themselves as fragments of memory.

Like old slides from a time gone by, logs bring possibleScapes that connect differently with each of the spectators.

Working together as a continuous system of gears, the algorithm is associated with the image bank, creating the most diverse interferences, revealing unique possibilities for experimenting with memory.

This is a commemorative token, for the participation of the "savedScapes" project (https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/16116) in the NFT SHOW EUROPE 2022 on the weekend of 17th and 18th September 2022.

As a thank you for all your support, "savedScapes" holders will have the right to mint the same number of editions for free.

The print with all holders will be done tomorrow (September 18th) at 10:00 BRT | 13:00 UTC | 15:00 CEST, and the token will open for collection after one hour at 11:00 am BRT | 14:00 UTC | 16:00 CEST.

Nothing is just one thing.

Generative Token by of Morbeck for fxhash

september 17, 2022

metadata.name: TRISTITIA #11
metadata.description:
TRISTITIA (sadness; melancholy) is my next generative experiment that explores the concept of loss. This is an experiment into the generation of void structures from 2D geometries. Alternating hard and soft edges create strange illusions of depth in the structure. 

TRISTITIA invites the audience to gaze deep into the abyss within and come up with your own interpretation of what it all means.

LICENSE: The code is released under CC-BY-SA 3.0, and acknowledges XORshift code from wikipedia (CC-BY-SA 3.0) and poisson disc sampling code by thecodingtrain (MIT)

- Press [ space ] or click to toggle animation

- Press [ s ] to save the current frame as a 3000x4000 PNG

Requires WebGL2
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Ex Mobius (Neon Red) #3
metadata.description:
Composed of layered PNGs.

Each output in this collection has the same "mobius" shape, but the number and positions of the colored regions varies.

Please allow up to 20 seconds for each image to fully load.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 3000x3000px PNG.

Several "Ex Mobius" collections will be released, each with a different color palette. All outputs in this collection will have the Neon Red color palette.

metadata.name: Green life in nature #110
metadata.description:
Green life in nature
We have forgotten to live in nature
Life in green area
The new world has swallowed us up
We have sold ourselves to the machines!
How long has it been since we stepped into the forest?
How long have we not been among the trees?
